he most far-reaching question" of philosophy. For Dewey, the pragmatic struggle for the good life required a willingness "to surrender the actual experienced good for a possible ideal good." Dewey's pragmatism helps us to understand the place of the transcendent ideal in a world of action and practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aIdealism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  ajohn dewey, ideal, transcendence, pragmatism, philosophy, human nature, reason, wallace stevens, michael oakeshott, hans-georg gadamer, religion, education, ethics, art, nonfiction, meaning, purpose, liminality, morality, moral action, decision making, good, sin, virtue, humanism, rationality, vorurteil, self, habit, faith, belief, truth, unseen, knowledge.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226818009423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226818009/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles